urne, Kent, England":"Leybourne, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Leybourne, Kent, England":"Leybourne, Kent, England","Mount Bures, Essex, England":"Mount Bures, Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Kent, England":"Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Essex, England":"Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Otley, Yorkshire, England":"Otley, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"about 1170–Abt 1223":"about 1170–about 1223","1165–1199":"1165–1199","1187–1261":"1187–1261","1190–1251":"1190–1251","1191–Female":"1191–Deceased","1170–1223":"1170–1223","1190":"1190","about 1170":"about 1170","1187":"1187","1165":"1165","1251":"1251","1261":"1261","1170":"1170","1191":"1191","Abt 1223":"about 1223","1223":"1223","1199":"1199","Abt 1192":"about 1192","Bef 1190":"before 1190","Leyburne, Kent, England":"Leybourne, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Leybourne, Kent, England":"Leybourne, Kent, England","Mount Bures, Essex, England":"Mount Bures, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","Essex, England":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","Otley, Yorkshire, England":"Otley, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Leybourne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Laybourne  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Laybourne","meanings":["English (northern): habitational name from Leyburn in Yorkshire. The placename probably derives from Old English <i>hlēg</i> ‘shelter’ + <i>burna</i> ‘spring, stream’."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Margaret De Leybourne was born about 1170, in Leybourne, Kent, England, United Kingdom. She married Robert de Leybourne about 1192, in Kent, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. She died about 1223, at the age of 55."},"et":{"about 1170–Abt 1223":"umbes 1170–umbes 1223","1165–1199":"1165–1199","1187–1261":"1187–1261","1190–1251":"1190–1251","1191–Female":"1191–Surnud","1170–1223":"1170–1223","1190":"1190","about 1170":"umbes 1170","1187":"1187","1165":"1165","1251":"1251","1261":"1261","1170":"1170","1191":"1191","Abt 1223":"umbes 1223","1223":"1223","1199":"1199","Abt 1192":"umbes 1192","Bef 1190":"enne 1190","Leyburne, Kent, England":"Leybourne, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Leybourne, Kent, England":"Leybourne, Kent, England","Mount Bures, Essex, England":"Mount Bures, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Essex, England":"Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Otley, Yorkshire, England":"Otley, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1170–Abt 1223":"noin 1170–noin 1223","1165–1199":"1165–1199","1187–1261":"1187–1261","1190–1251":"1190–1251","1191–Female":"1191–Kuollut","1170–1223":"1170–1223","1190":"1190","about 1170":"noin 1170","1187":"1187","1165":"1165","1251":"1251","1261":"1261","1170":"1170","1191":"1191","Abt 1223":"noin 1223","1223":"1223","1199":"1199","Abt 1192":"noin 1192","Bef 1190":"ennen vuotta 1